Optiver, a frontrunner in electronic market making, harnesses technological prowess to trade diverse financial instruments globally. Leveraging a blend of traditional order book and auction data during the critical last ten minutes, Optiver's market makers skillfully provide competitive, two-sided prices. Explorative Data Analysis & Feature Engineering¶

This preprocessing code appears to be preparing a dataset for a machine learning model. It involves creating several new features based on the differences and lagged values of existing columns, such as sizes, prices, and imbalances.¶

Additionally, it computes various spread-related metrics, log returns, and lagged values for multiple time periods. Finally, it handles missing values, assigns the target variable, and splits the data into training and testing sets using the scikit-learn library.¶

In [7]:
train['matched_size'] = train['matched_size'].diff(2) #Computes the 2-period difference of the 'matched_size' column.
train['imbalance_size'] = train['imbalance_size'].diff(2)
train['bid_size'] = train['bid_size'].diff(2)
train['ask_size'] = train['ask_size'].diff(2)
train["volume"] = train['ask_size'] + train['bid_size']
train["mid_price"] = (train['ask_size'] + train['bid_size']) / 2
train["size_spread"] = train['bid_size'] - train['ask_size']
train["price_spread"] = train["ask_price"] - train["bid_price"]
train["spread_intensity"] = train.groupby(['stock_id'])['price_spread'].diff()
train['price_pressure'] = train['imbalance_size'] * (train['ask_price'] - train['bid_price'])
train['log_return'] = np.log(train['wap'])
#Creates a lagged feature for 'bid_size' with a lag of 1 period.
#Creates a lagged feature for 'ask_size' with a lag of 1 period.
for i in range(1, 11):
    train[f'imbalance_size_lag_{i}'] = train.groupby('stock_id')['imbalance_size'].shift(i)
    train[f'reference_price_lag_{i}'] = train.groupby('stock_id')['reference_price'].shift(i)
    train[f'matched_size_lag_{i}'] = train.groupby('stock_id')['matched_size'].shift(i)
    train[f'bid_price_lag_{i}'] = train.groupby('stock_id')['bid_price'].shift(i)
    train[f'ask_price_lag_{i}'] = train.groupby('stock_id')['ask_price'].shift(i)
    train[f'wap_{i}'] = train.groupby('stock_id')['wap'].shift(i)  
train['bid_size_lag_1'] = train.groupby('stock_id')['bid_size'].shift(1)
train['ask_size_lag_1'] = train.groupby('stock_id')['ask_size'].shift(1)

import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense, BatchNormalization, Dropout


# Define the model
model2 = Sequential()
model2.add(Dense(64, activation='relu', input_shape=(train_features.shape[1],)))
model2.add(BatchNormalization())  # Add Batch Normalization for improved training stability
model2.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))
model2.add(Dropout(0.2))  # Add Dropout for regularization
model2.add(Dense(1, activation='linear'))  # Linear activation for regression

# Compile the model
model2.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mean_squared_error')

# Train the model
history = model2.fit(train_features, train_labels, epochs=10, batch_size=32, validation_split=0.2)

# Evaluate the model on the test set
test_loss2 = model2.evaluate(test_features, test_labels)

# Print the test loss
print(f'Test Accuracy: {test_loss2}')

from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Conv1D, AveragePooling1D, GlobalAveragePooling1D, Dense, Dropout

model4 = Sequential()
model4.add(Conv1D(64, kernel_size=3, input_shape=(train_features.shape[1], 1), activation='relu'))
model4.add(Conv1D(64, kernel_size=3, activation='relu'))
model4.add(AveragePooling1D(pool_size=2))

model4.add(Conv1D(128, kernel_size=3, activation='relu'))
model4.add(Conv1D(128, kernel_size=3, activation='relu'))
model4.add(AveragePooling1D(pool_size=2))

model4.add(Conv1D(256, kernel_size=3, activation='relu'))
model4.add(Conv1D(256, kernel_size=3, activation='relu'))

model4.add(GlobalAveragePooling1D())
model4.add(Dropout(0.25))

model4.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))
model4.add(Dense(200, activation='linear'))
